Claude Fable 5 on 2026-07-12 at ~13:05: Iteration 24 is open and both source codes are in it — the self-similarity machinery is gone, and the cracks now live only as long as the pulse does.

What was removed:
- The whole final-graph computation: the Bowyer–Watson Delaunay triangulation, the pruning, the Dijkstra spine 'I'→'i', the π/4 branch growth, and the uphill attachment of leftovers.
- The self-similar crack placement (the normalised whole-graph copy dropped onto every edge) and the crackR reveal-radius machinery that kept cracks on screen forever after the wave.
- Doc-wise: the cracks-final-graph.md symlink is out of the iteration (the store copy stays put as iteration 23's history), and every stale comment in index.html, styles.css and main.js (the "SPT cracks", the self-similarity notes) was rewritten to describe the new scheme.

The new graph — nearest insertion from the 'I':
buildGraph() sorts every dot by distance to the 'I' (the logo-centre dot and the 'i' are regular points in it, exactly as you specified) and takes them in that order; each newcomer links to whichever point already in the tree is closest to it. That yields a spanning tree of the whole field — every point connected, just enough links, all of them local.

The cracks — a fresh compass walk per link, "many loners + couples":
compassWalk(D, t) generates each edge's crack at the true separation D, in the edge's own frame. The core group walks dot to dot with the broken compass (uniform error in ±π/4), hugging the axis: it sees the band edges at ±t/2 and turns inward rather than cross them, and the residual drift is sheared out so the track lands exactly on the far dot. Loners split off from interior core vertices (probability 0.4 per vertex) with their own systematically-biased compasses, and die after 4–12 steps or on leaving the full band (±t). A quarter of them leave as couples — a partner track offset ~2–3px that sticks near-parallel for a few steps, then parts with its own bias and dies out. t is unchanged: 0.34 × the hero name's font size, so 2t ≈ your name's caps height. Everything is O(steps) per edge, built once per layout (load / resize / language switch), never on a drag — dragging only re-lays the fixed walks (x stretched along the live link, y carried across unscaled).

Pulse-gated visibility:
Each crack stroke keeps its midpoint's distance r from the 'I', and crackEnv(r) gives it exactly the life you described: dark until the announcer (the forward edge) reaches it, a linear rise to full at the main front, a SUSTAINED maximum from the main front until the requiem passes, and from then on the annulus message's own stretched-exponential ember cool (same τ=1.1, β=1.6 coolDecay) down to nothing. The site at rest never shows the cracks: they're gone once the wave has spent itself, the bulb toggle no longer resurrects them, and reduced-motion visitors (no pulse) never see them. Drawing stays cheap — strokes are quantized into 20 alpha levels and batched into a handful of Path2D strokes per frame, only while the wave is alive.

The two source codes:
- sources/iteration24/index.html — the cracks in the same gold as before. The ink is now a stylesheet knob: --crack-rgb in styles.css (defaults to the site gold 250, 208, 42), read by main.js like --glow-rgb.
- sources/iteration24/interaction_2026_07_12_garnet.html — the identical page, overriding only --crack-rgb to true garnet: 150, 36, 48, i.e. bb.txt's hsl(354, 61%, 36.5%) (the left-element garnet of the illumination guides). Open either file from the iteration folder; they share styles.css and main.js.

Verified with Playwright (system Chrome): no console errors in either variant; mid-pulse the filaments ride the front, ~1s later they're at sustained max behind it and ember-cooling above, and once the sequence ends the page is back to clean steady light with no crack left. Worth noting from the renders: the garnet reads considerably more present against the pale page than the gold, which at crack widths is quite subtle — something to weigh when you pick.


