Claude Fable 5 on 2026-07-12 at ~14:10: Everything is in. The doc is gone for real this time, both load bugs are diagnosed and fixed, the cracks now live in the Lipschitz diamond with join-on-cross isles, the knob sheet is in the iteration folder, the variant is wrist-red, and the milestone is crossed.

The documentation — my miss. Last turn I only removed iteration 24's symlink and left the store file, over-cautiously treating assets/ as untouchable archive. Both assets/cracks-final-graph.md and iteration 23's now-dangling symlink to it are deleted; git history keeps them.

The Firefox bug (only 'I' + centre dots, cracks to the top-left corner). Root cause found: reflect.js wraps every text node on the page into .litw word spans, and its first prep races main.js's first layout — main.js schedules a requestAnimationFrame(draw) at parse time, and draw() hands the field to reflect.js, which wraps. When the wrap won the race (browser/load dependent — hence "half the time", and Firefox-leaning), contactAnchor()'s firstChild-is-text check failed, so the 'i' dot was never positioned: it sat at the .points container origin — the page's top-left corner. The band clamp then read yBot ≈ 0 and dropped every scattered point, leaving exactly the two exempt dots ('I', centre) plus a crack running into the corner where the unpositioned 'i' node sat. Fixed: contactAnchor now walks the head's TEXT NODES (wrap-proof, works before or after reflect.js gets there), and the clamp only trusts the bottom bound once the 'i' has actually been anchored.

The Chrome y-dance. The browser restores the remembered scroll on reload, and THEN our late layout work lands (the lede-clear spacer, the logo margin fix, the 300 ms relayout), changing the page height under the restored offset — so the view shifts as if scrolled, and each F5 saves the shifted offset and compounds it. Fixed with history.scrollRestoration = "manual": the load sequence is built from the top anyway, so every load now starts there, deterministically.

The cracks, reworked (after reading how they were formed):
- Geometry as you defined it: the walk runs (0,0)→(D,0) in the edge frame inside the band ±h (h is the old t: 0.34 × the hero name's font size, 2h ≈ its caps). The MAIN SPINE was and stays bounded to the half-band ±h/2; loners may roam out to the full ±h and fall.
- Lipschitz birth and death: the whole crack is now confined to |y| ≤ λ·min(x, D−x), with λ chosen so the top line passes through (D/2, h) — your two cones, which together with the band make a diamond (the ±h cap is exactly attained at the midpoint). Rather than re-rolling, the core keeps its edge-avoiding behaviour against the shrinking bound (turn inward, clamped if the pinch is tighter than a π/4 turn can follow), and the far vertex is the diamond's apex itself — so every crack is born AT one dot and converges INTO the other, and no shear correction is needed any more.
- Join-on-cross: a loner (or a couple's partner) whose step crosses the core polyline now ENDS at the crossing point — no more agency — closing the isle. Falling off the diamond still kills a track; running out of steps still ends it quietly.
- Knobs, gathered into one CRK block in main.js and CHOSEN: STEP 14 (nominal step px), JIT 0.5 (loner wobble as a fraction of the π/4 error), LON_P 0.4 (loner spawn per core vertex), life 4–12 steps, CPL_P 0.25 (couples). The sheet interaction_2026_07_12_cracks-knobs.png in the iteration folder shows 10 bands (laid down, width = 5 × height, dot to dot, the diamond and half-band drawn as faint guides): the chosen set plus sparse/dense loners, short/long lives, no/abundant couples, wilder jitter, and long/short strides — pick for the wrap-up and I'll set it.
- Finer stroke: the width scale dropped from 0.6+0.28·s to 0.45+0.2·s, and the core/loner widths from 0.9/0.55 to 0.75/0.45 of it.

The red. Sampled from the page's own render of the photo at the spot you described — the top part of the seam between the two bottom squares of the 2×3 tiling — where the wrist band reads rgb(228, 75, 69) at its saturated core (hue ≈ 2°, against the old garnet's 354° whose blue lean is what read purple). interaction_2026_07_12_garnet.html now overrides --crack-rgb to that; rendered, it reads unmistakably warm red.

Milestones: "Lightning connections cast their own light…" is crossed, linked to iteration 24. Five phrasings for the new milestone — the pulse-reveal as a wink at your point-cloud years — pick or remix:
1. The pulse momentarily reveals the connections hiding between the illuminating points — a wink at what my research has been about: understanding the underlying connections inside point clouds
2. Cracks flash with the pulse, briefly exposing how the scattered points connect — the way my work has been to uncover the structure latent in a point cloud
3. For the pulse's lifetime the site shows its skeleton — the graph joining its points — an echo of years spent finding the structure hiding in point clouds
4. The ignition wave uncovers, for a moment, the network that ties the point field together, then lets it cool away — a nod to my years teasing connections out of point clouds
5. A passing pulse betrays the connections between the illuminating points before they fade to black — like my day job: making the invisible relations inside a point cloud visible for a moment

Verified in Chrome (Playwright): no console errors on either source; scrollRestoration reads "manual"; a simulated pre-wrapped contact head plus forced relayout still anchors the 'i' dot on the head (page-y within its line, not the origin); mid-pulse the finer cracks ride the wave and converge into the dots, and the page is clean of them once the sequence ends. I could not drive system Firefox (Playwright needs its own build), but the fixed race is browser-independent — the wrapped-head simulation covers the failing path itself.


